{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471683"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:50:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:50:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"384"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/384"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.03,0.03,0,0.8]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"384"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86768"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/384"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"384"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71038"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"128"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15"},{"type":"contributions","id":"99"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86768"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of chest pain. She has been unwell with a sore throat and runny nose for the past week. The chest pain is located in the substernal region, worse on deep inspiration and lying supine, and improves when sitting forward. It does not radiate to her arm or jaw. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 80/min and regular, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 38.0\u00b0C. A friction rub is auscultated over the left lower sternal border region and is loudest at the end of expiration. Her jugular venous pressure is normal. Heart sounds are dual with no murmurs. Chest is clear to auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Viral myocarditis","Dressler syndrome","Costochondritis","Acute coronary syndrome","Acute pericarditis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of acute \u003Cstrong\u003Epericarditis\u003C/strong\u003E: pleuritic chest pain that worsens when supine and improves on sitting forward, following a likely viral upper respiratory tract infection. The presence of a pericardial friction rub is highly specific (though not sensitive) for pericarditis. The patient\u0027s age and recent viral illness make post-viral pericarditis the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral myocarditis\u003C/strong\u003E can co-exist with pericarditis (myopericarditis) but typically presents with symptoms of heart failure, arrhythmias, or troponin elevation rather than the characteristic pleuritic pain. A friction rub would not be present in isolated myocarditis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDressler syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (post-cardiac injury syndrome) causes a similar clinical picture but occurs 2-6 weeks after cardiac surgery, myocardial infarction, or other cardiac trauma. This patient has no history of cardiac injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECostochondritis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause chest wall pain that is worse with breathing, but the pain is reproducible on palpation of the costochondral joints, and there would be no friction rub or fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute coronary syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is extremely rare in teenagers without risk factors. The pain would typically be crushing or heavy rather than pleuritic, and would not vary with position. There would be no friction rub.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next steps would include an ECG (which may show widespread ST elevation and PR depression), inflammatory markers, and cardiac biomarkers to assess for associated myocarditis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pericarditis commonly presents with pleuritic chest pain that worsens when supine, often following a viral illness.","A pericardial friction rub is highly specific for pericarditis, though not sensitive.","Post-viral pericarditis is more common in young patients than other cardiac causes of chest pain."],"references":["Tingle LE, Molina D, Calvert CW. Acute pericarditis. Am Fam Physician. 2007 Nov 15;76(10):1509-14. PMID: 18052017.","Rahman A, Saraswat A. Pericarditis. Aust Fam Physician. 2017;46(11):810-814."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71038"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"384"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71038"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-24T16:54:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-24T16:55:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"384"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86768"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1